-- cell-zero.cell: minimal evaluation kernel
-- This is the metacircular evaluator for Cell, written in Cell.
--
-- cell-zero is a Cell program that evaluates other Cell programs.
-- It can be executed by an LLM directly (reading this file as
-- instructions) or by a classical runtime that interprets it.
--
-- This is a SKETCH — not yet executable. It demonstrates the
-- structure and metacircular property.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- PHASE 1: Graph Inspection
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ read-graph
  given §program
  yield cells[], edges[]

  ∴ Parse «§program» as a Cell program.
    Extract all cell declarations (⊢ blocks) into «cells».
    Extract all dependency edges (given cell→output) into «edges».
    Do NOT execute any cell — treat everything as data.

  ⊨ each cell in cells has: name, givens[], yields[], body, oracles[]
  ⊨ each edge in edges has: from-cell, from-output, to-cell

⊢ check-inputs
  given read-graph→cells
  given read-graph→edges
  given §state
  yield ready-cells[], blocked-cells[]

  ∴ For each cell in «cells», check whether all its given inputs
    are bound in «§state» (have a ≡ value).

    A cell is READY if: all givens are bound AND the cell is not
    yet frozen (no yield ≡ in state).

    A cell is BLOCKED if: any given is unbound.

    Check ⊥ status: if any given input is ⊥, check for ⊥? handler.

  ⊨ ready-cells ∪ blocked-cells = cells
  ⊨ every cell in ready-cells has all givens bound in §state

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- PHASE 2: Evaluation
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ pick-cell
  given check-inputs→ready-cells
  yield §target

  ∴ Choose one cell from «ready-cells» to evaluate.
    Prefer cells with fewer dependencies (leaf-first).
    If multiple cells are equally ready, any choice is valid
    (confluence guarantees the result is the same).

  ⊨ §target ∈ ready-cells

⊢ evaluate
  given pick-cell→§target
  given §state
  yield tentative-outputs[], §target-with-outputs

  ∴ Evaluate «§target»:
    - If it has a ∴ body: interpret the natural language instruction
      using the bound given values from «§state». Produce outputs.
    - If it has a ⊢= body: compute the deterministic expression.
      Produce exact outputs.
    - Do NOT freeze the cell yet. The outputs are TENTATIVE.

  ⊨ |tentative-outputs| = |§target.yields|
  ⊨ §target-with-outputs preserves §target's structure

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- PHASE 3: Oracle Checking (the claim cell protocol)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ spawn-claims
  given evaluate→tentative-outputs
  given pick-cell→§target
  yield §claim-cells[]

  ∴ For each oracle (⊨) on «§target», create a claim cell:
    The claim cell checks whether the tentative output satisfies
    the oracle condition.

    Deterministic oracles (exact value checks) produce cells with
    ⊢= bodies. Semantic oracles produce cells with ∴ bodies.

  ⊨ |§claim-cells| = |§target.oracles|
  ⊨ each claim cell references the tentative output

⊢ check-claims
  given spawn-claims→§claim-cells
  yield all-pass, failed-oracles[], retry-context

  ∴ Evaluate each claim cell in «§claim-cells».
    Collect pass/fail results.
    If any fail, include the failure context for retry.

  ⊢= all-pass ← |failed-oracles| = 0
  ⊢= retry-context ← if all-pass then "" else
    "Previous attempt failed oracles: " ++
    join(failed-oracles, ", ")

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- PHASE 4: Commit or Retry
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ decide
  given check-claims→all-pass
  given check-claims→retry-context
  given pick-cell→§target
  given evaluate→tentative-outputs
  yield action, §updated-state

  ∴ Based on the oracle results:

    If «all-pass»:
      FREEZE: bind the tentative outputs as yield ≡ values
      in the program state. The cell is now frozen.

    If not «all-pass» and retries remain (check ⊨? on failure):
      RETRY: rewrite §target with «retry-context» appended
      to the ∴ body. Do not freeze. Return to check-inputs.

    If not «all-pass» and retries exhausted (check ⊨? on exhaustion):
      BOTTOM: freeze §target with all outputs = ⊥.
      Or apply the exhaustion policy (error-value, partial-accept).

  ⊨ action ∈ {"freeze", "retry", "bottom"}
  ⊨ if action = "freeze" then §updated-state has new yield ≡ bindings
  ⊨ if action = "bottom" then §updated-state has yield ≡ ⊥ bindings

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- PHASE 5: Bottom Handling
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ handle-bottom
  given decide→§updated-state
  given check-inputs→blocked-cells
  yield §state-after-bottom

  ∴ After a cell is frozen (possibly with ⊥ outputs), check
    downstream cells for ⊥? handlers.

    For each blocked cell that depends on a newly-⊥ output:
    - If it has ⊥? skip with: freeze it with the skip values
    - If it has ⊥? error-value(⊥): freeze it with ⊥
    - If it has no ⊥? handler: leave it blocked (⊥ propagates
      naturally — the cell is never ready)

  ⊨ §state-after-bottom extends §updated-state (only adds bindings)

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- PHASE 6: The Loop (spawner — never terminates)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢⊢ eval-loop
  given §program
  yield §final-state
  until check-inputs→ready-cells is empty

  ∴ This is the evaluation loop. Starting from «§program»:
    1. read-graph → cells, edges
    2. check-inputs → ready-cells
    3. If ready-cells is empty → quiesce (return current state)
    4. pick-cell → §target
    5. evaluate → tentative outputs
    6. spawn-claims → claim cells
    7. check-claims → pass/fail
    8. decide → freeze/retry/bottom
    9. handle-bottom → update state
    10. Go to 2

    This loop never truly terminates — spawners (⊢⊢) in the
    program can add new cells, oracle checking adds claim cells,
    and ⊥ handling can trigger new evaluations.

    The loop QUIESCES when no cells are ready. But new inputs
    or external events can wake it.

  ⊨ §final-state extends §program (only adds yield ≡ bindings)
  ⊨ §final-state preserves all frozen values from §program

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- METACIRCULAR PROPERTY
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- cell-zero IS a Cell program. It can evaluate itself:
--
--   eval-loop(§cell-zero) → evaluates cell-zero's own cells
--
-- This produces a fixed point: cell-zero evaluating cell-zero
-- produces... cell-zero's evaluation behavior.
--
-- In practice, the bootstrap sequence is:
-- 1. A substrate (LLM or runtime) reads cell-zero.cell
-- 2. It follows cell-zero's instructions to evaluate a target program
-- 3. cell-zero's cells (read-graph, check-inputs, etc.) are
--    themselves evaluated by the substrate
-- 4. Some of these cells can be crystallized (check-inputs, pick-cell)
-- 5. Others must stay soft forever (evaluate, check-claims for semantic oracles)
--
-- The substrate is to cell-zero what the CPU is to a Scheme REPL.
-- cell-zero is to user programs what the REPL is to Scheme programs.
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
